titleproper.value: Guide to the Fales Manuscript Collection <lb/><date>circa 1700-2000 </date><lb/> <num>MSS.001</num>

author.value: Collection processed by Tania Friedel, Philip Lauer, Marvin J. Taylor, 1998-2000. Revised by Julia Lloyd, 2007, and Colin Wells, 2009.

creation.value: This finding aid was produced using ArchivesSpace <date>2019-04-11T14:37:49</date>

abstract.value: The Fales Manuscript collection is made up of some 50,000 items, much of which was assembled by DeCoursey Fales from 1908-1966 and donated to NYU. The provenance of the materials is complicated, however. Following Fales' death in 1966, other collections and purchases were added into the Fales Manuscripts collection. We do not have a comprehensive listing of what Fales owned and what the library later purchased after his death. The collection consists of correspondence, manuscripts, drawings, photographs, realia, ephemera, and other materials primarily about English and American authors from 1700 to the present. There are special strenths in the Victorian, Edwardian, English 1890s, and Transition Period writers.

p.value: Open for research without restrictions. Appointments are necessary to consult manuscript and archival materials.

Published citations should take the
following form:<lb/><lb/>
Identification of item,  date (if known); The Fales Manuscript Collection; MSS 001; box number; folder number; Fales Library and Special Collections, New York University Libraries.

De Coursey Fales (1888-1966) was a lawyer, banker, collector, bibliophile and yachtsman. In the last years of his life, Fales devoted himself full-time to collecting. Fales' collecting started with Walter Scott materials, and around that core, his collection grew to around 50,000 items pertaining to various authors spanning the 18th and 20th centuries. He began donating parts of that collection to New York University in 1957, and portions of his collection were also donated to the New York Public Library, Manhattan College, and the Morgan Library (of which he was a life fellow).

The Fales Manuscripts are arranged by size into three groups: Legal; Flat and Dickensiana; and Letter. Sometimes entire discrete collections are included within this collection (see for example the Tom Clark Papers, the Frank Harris Papers, the Provincetown Players Archive).

in 1994, this section subtitled "6. Redoing Childhood: The Beginning of the History of Dreams". The copy displays
copies of corrections in Acker's hand, as well as some marginal notation added in an unknown hand. The photocopy
was prepared for a recording session of Ms. Acker reading, backed by the female Thrash band "The Tribades"! and is inscribed by Acker in red ink on the cover page "for Susie - all my love, Acker the Pirate". </p><p>2. Autograph Note from Acker to the musical director, Ralph Carney, with a large ink drawing of an angry face.</p><p>3. 18pp. photocopied typescript entitled "Before the Days of Dreaming" with the indication that is was a "possible text for record".</p><p>4. A photocopy of a letter from Acker to the producer Hal Wilner regarding both of the included texts.</p></scopecontent></c><c id="aspace_ref24" level="otherlevel" otherlevel="unspecified"><did><unittitle>Acton, Harold</unittitle><unitid audience="internal" identifier="52043" type="Archivists Toolkit Database::RESOURCE_COMPONENT">52043</unitid><unitdate normal="1690/2000" type="inclusive">undated</unitdate><container altrender="Manuscript box -
